Package org.opensextant.giscore.events

Class Style

java.lang.Object
org.opensextant.giscore.events.AbstractObject
org.opensextant.giscore.events.StyleSelector
org.opensextant.giscore.events.Style
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable, IGISObject, VisitableGeometry, IDataSerializable
public class Style extends StyleSelector
Represents style information for points and lines. This information is used by the rendering code to emit the correct information for the output format.

Generic information from a KML reference.

Color and opacity (alpha) values are expressed in hexadecimal notation. The range of values for any one color is 0 to 255 (00 to ff). For alpha, 00 is fully transparent and ff is fully opaque. The order of expression is aabbggrr, where aa=alpha (00 to ff); bb=blue (00 to ff); gg=green (00 to ff); rr=red (00 to ff). For example, if you want to apply a blue color with 50 percent opacity to an overlay, you would specify the following: <color>7fff0000</color>, where alpha=0x7f, blue=0xff, green=0x00, and red=0x00.

Values for <colorMode> are normal (no effect) and random. A value of random applies a random linear scale to the base <color>}as follows.

Notes/Limitations:

Some less common tags (e.g. hotSpot in IconStyle and ItemIcon in ListStyle) are not currently supported.

Author:
DRAND, J.Mathews

    • setIconStyle

      public void setIconStyle(Color color, Double scale, String url)
      Set the icon style information
      Parameters:
      color - the color for the icon, can be null if want to use default color.
      scale - the scale of the icon, nullable (1.0=normal size of icon, 2.0=twice normal size, etc.)
      url - the url of the icon, nullable. If url is empty string or blank then an empty Icon element would appear in KML output. If null then no <Icon> will appear in IconStyle (using default icon).

    • setIconStyle

      public void setIconStyle(Color color, Double scale, Double heading, String url)
      Set the icon style information
      Parameters:
      color - the color for the icon, can be null if want to use default color.
      scale - the scale of the icon, nullable (1.0=normal size of icon, 2.0=twice normal size, etc.)
      heading - heading (i.e. icon rotation) in degrees. Default=0 (North). Values range from 0 to 360 degrees, nullable.
      url - the url of the icon, nullable. If url is blank or empty string then an empty Icon element would appear in corresponding KML output. If null then no <Icon> will appear in IconStyle (using default icon).

    • getIconUrl

      public String getIconUrl()
      Get URL associated with IconStyle.
      Returns:
      the url of the icon (non-empty or null value) If null then IconStyle did not have Icon element. If value is non-null then IconStyle should have an associated Icon element present.

      If icon URL is empty string then this indicates the href element was omitted, an empty element or value was an empty string.
      All 3 of these cases are handled the same in Google Earth which suppresses showing an icon. 

                               1. <IconStyle>
                         <Icon/>
                         </IconStyle>

                         2. <Icon>
                         <href/>
                         </Icon>

                         3. <Icon>
                         <href></href>
                         </Icon>

    • setBalloonStyle

      public void setBalloonStyle(Color bgColor, String text, Color textColor, String displayMode)
      Set the balloon style
      Parameters:
      bgColor - the color for the balloon background, if null will use default color: opaque white (ffffffff).
      text - the textual template for the balloon content
      textColor - the color for the text in the balloon. The default is black (ff000000).
      displayMode - If displayMode is "default", Google Earth uses the information supplied in text to create a balloon . If displayMode is "hide", Google Earth does not display the balloon. "default" is the default value if null, blank or empty string value is supplied.

    • getBalloonBgColor

      public Color getBalloonBgColor()
      Valid if hasBalloonStyle returns true.
      Returns:
      the bgColor, background color of the balloon (optional). Color and opacity (alpha) values are expressed in hexadecimal notation. The range of values for any one color is 0 to 255 (00 to ff). The order of expression is aabbggrr, where aa=alpha (00 to ff); bb=blue (00 to ff); gg=green (00 to ff); rr=red (00 to ff). For alpha, 00 is fully transparent and ff is fully opaque. For example, if you want to apply a blue color with 50 percent opacity to an overlay, you would specify the following: <bgColor>7fff0000</bgColor>, where alpha=0x7f, blue=0xff, green=0x00, and red=0x00. The default is opaque white (ffffffff).

    • getBalloonText

      public String getBalloonText()
      Valid if hasBalloonStyle returns true.
      Returns:
      the text, Text displayed in the balloon. If no text is specified, Google Earth draws the default balloon (with the Feature name in boldface, the Feature description, links for driving directions, a white background, and a tail that is attached to the point coordinates of the Feature, if specified).

    • getBalloonTextColor

      public Color getBalloonTextColor()
      Valid if hasBalloonStyle returns true.
      Returns:
      the balloonTextColor, foreground color for text. The default is black (ff000000).

    • getBalloonDisplayMode

      public String getBalloonDisplayMode()
      Valid if hasBalloonStyle returns true.
      Returns:
      the balloonDisplayMode, If displayMode is 'default', Google Earth uses the information supplied in text to create a balloon . If displayMode is 'hide', Google Earth does not display the balloon. In Google Earth, clicking the List View icon for a Placemark whose balloon's displayMode is 'hide' causes Google Earth to fly to the Placemark.
